  <h4 class="pHead4" >
</h4>    

<a name="wp3689072"> </a><h3 class="pHead3" >
Description
</h3>    

<a name="wp3689073"> </a><p class="pBody" >
The <code class="cCodeBody">assert_no_overflow</code> assertion checker checks the expression <span style="font-style: oblique" class="cCodeBodyEmphasis">test_expr</span> at each rising edge of <span style="font-style: oblique" class="cCodeBodyEmphasis">clk</span> to determine if its value has changed from a value (at the previous rising edge of <span style="font-style: oblique" class="cCodeBodyEmphasis">clk</span><span style="font-style: normal" class="cCodeBodyEmphasis">) </span>that was equal to <span style="font-style: oblique" class="cCodeBodyEmphasis">max</span>. If so, the checker verifies that the new value has not overflowed <span style="font-style: oblique" class="cCodeBodyEmphasis">max</span>. That is, it verifies the value of <span style="font-style: oblique" class="cCodeBodyEmphasis">test_expr</span> is not greater than <span style="font-style: oblique" class="cCodeBodyEmphasis">max</span> or less than or equal to <span style="font-style: oblique" class="cCodeBodyEmphasis">min</span> (in which case, the assertion fails).
</p>    
<a name="wp3690252"> </a><p class="pBody" >
The checker is useful for verifying counters, where it can ensure the counter does not wrap from the highest value to the lowest value in a specified range. For example, it can be used to check that memory structure pointers do not wrap around. For a more general test for overflow, use <code class="cCodeBody">assert_delta</code> or <code class="cCodeBody">assert_fifo_index</code>.
</p>    
<a name="wp3690213"> </a><p class="pBody" >

</p>    
<a name="wp3689082"> </a><h4 class="pHead4" >
Assertion Check  </h4>    <div align="left" class="tbl">
<table border="0">
  <caption></caption>
  <tr align="left" valign="top">    <td><a name="wp3689077"> </a><div class="pCellBodyLeft" >
&#160;
